05495nam a22006735i 9780773569751DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20032003xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807735697517 a10.1515/97807735697512doi  a(DE-B1597)655647  a(OCoLC)1320900011  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aQH26bH68 2003eb 7aHIS0060002bisacsh04a508/.092/2411 aHouston, Stuart, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aEighteenth-Century Naturalists of Hudson Bay /cStuart Houston, Tim Ball, Mary Houston. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2003] 4c©2003  a1 online resource (360 p.) :b8 colour and 25 black an white illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aMcGill-Queen's Indigenous and Northern Studies ;v3400tFront Matter -- tContents -- tIllustrations -- tTables -- tAcknowledgments -- tSupplementary Natural History Documents -- tAbbreviations -- tForeword -- tIntroduction -- tThe European Connection -- tAlexander Light -- tJames Isham (1716–1761) -- tHumphrey Marten (1729?–1790?) -- tAndrew Graham (1733–1815) -- tThomas Hutghins (1742?–1790) -- tMoses Norton (1735?–1773) -- tSamuel Hearne (1745–1792) -- tPeter Fidler (1769–1822) -- tNatural History -- tClimatology -- tIn Striking Contrast: Charles Town -- tAppendices -- tSailing Ships to York Factory, 1716–1892 -- tProvenance of HBC Journals -- tThe Ten Graham/Hutghins Manuscripts in the HBG Archives: A Detective Story -- tHudson’s Bay Company Fur Catches Demonstrate Ten-Year Cycles -- tThe Nineteenth-Century Trade in Swan Skins and Quills -- tHow did the Canada Goose Get its Name Before There was a Canada? -- tCree Names in Use at Hudson Bay in the Eighteenth Century -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe authors show that meteorologic data and weather information recorded at the HBC trading posts over two centuries provide the largest and longest consecutive series available anywhere in North America, one that can help us understand the mechanisms and amount of climate change. They demonstrate that Hudson Bay is the second largest site of new bird species named by Linnaeus and reproduce some of George Edwards' colour paintings of these new species. Six informative appendices reveal how the invaluable HBC archives were transferred from London, England, to Winnipeg, correct previous misinterpretations of the collaboration and relative contributions of Thomas Hutchins and Andrew Graham, use two centuries of HBC fur returns to demonstrate the ten-year hare and lynx cycles, tell how the swan trade almost extirpated the Trumpeter Swan, explain how the Canada Goose got its name before there was a Canada, and offer an extensive list of eighteenth-century Cree names for birds, mammals, and fish. Informative tables list the eighteenth-century surgeons at York Factory and give names and dates for the annual supply ships.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aHudson's Bay Company-Biography. 0aNaturalists-Great Britain-Biography. 0aNaturalists-Hudson Bay Region-Biography. 7aHISTORY / Canada / General.2bisacsh1 aBall, Tim, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aHouston, C. Stuart, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHouston, Mary I., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHouston, Mary, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aHouston, Mary, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHouston, Stuart, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOkimâsis¹, Jean, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabu